nvex polygon">Convex</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_p=
olygon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cyclic polygon">cyclic</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_polygon" title=3D"Equilateral=
 polygon">equilateral</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isogona=
l_figure" title=3D"Isogonal figure">isogonal</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Isotoxal_figure" title=3D"Isotoxal figure">isotoxal</a></td=
></tr></tbody></table></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D=
"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, a <b>regular polygon</b> is a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" title=3D"Polygon">polygon=
</a> that is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equiangular_polygon" =
title=3D"Equiangular polygon">direct equiangular</a> (all angles are equal =
in measure) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_polygo=
n" title=3D"Equilateral polygon">equilateral</a> (all sides have the same l=
ength). Regular polygons may be either <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygon">convex</a></i> or <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_polygon" title=3D"Star polygon">st=
ar</a></i>. In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathemat=
ics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limit</a>, a sequence of regular polygo=
ns with an increasing number of sides approximates a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a>, if the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perimeter" title=3D"Perimeter">perimeter</a> o=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a> is=
 fixed, or a regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apeirogon" ti=
tle=3D"Apeirogon">apeirogon</a> (effectively a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">straight line</a>),=
 if the edge length is fixed.
</p>
