symbols</figcaption></figure>
<p>These properties apply to all regular polygons, whether convex or <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_polygon" title=3D"Star polygon">sta=
r</a>:
</p>
<ul><li>A regular <i>n</i>-sided polygon has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rotational_symmetry" title=3D"Rotational symmetry">rotational sy=
mmetry</a> of order <i>n</i>.</li></ul>
<ul><li>All vertices of a regular polygon lie on a common circle (the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumscribed_circle" title=3D"Circumsc=
ribed circle">circumscribed circle</a>); i.e., they are concyclic points. T=
hat is, a regular polygon is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyc=
lic_polygon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cyclic polygon">cyclic polygon<=
/a>.</li></ul>
<ul><li>Together with the property of equal-length sides, this implies that=
 every regular polygon also has an inscribed circle or <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incircle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Incircle">inc=
ircle</a> that is tangent to every side at the midpoint. Thus a regular pol=
ygon is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangential_polygon" titl=
e=3D"Tangential polygon">tangential polygon</a>.</li></ul>
<ul><li>A regular <i>n</i>-sided polygon can be constructed with <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass_and_straightedge" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Compass and straightedge">compass and straightedge</a> if and =
only if the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odd_number" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Odd number">odd</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime</a> factors of <i>n</i> a=
re distinct <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat_prime" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fermat prime">Fermat primes</a>. <span role=3D"note"=
 class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable crossreference">(See <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructible_polygon" title=3D"Constructibl=
e polygon">constructible polygon</a>.)</span></li></ul>
<ul><li>A regular <i>n</i>-sided polygon can be constructed with <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Origami" title=3D"Origami">origami</a> if an=
d only if <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cl=
