<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Symmetry">Symmetry</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_polygon&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Symmetry"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry_group" title=3D"Sy=
mmetry group">symmetry group</a> of an <i>n</i>-sided regular polygon is th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dihedral_group" title=3D"Dihedra=
l group">dihedral group</a> D<sub><i>n</i></sub> (of order 2<i>n</i>): D<su=
b>2</sub>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dihedral_group_of_order=
_6" title=3D"Dihedral group of order 6">D<sub>3</sub></a>, D<sub>4</sub>, .=
.. It consists of the rotations in C<sub><i>n</i></sub>, together with <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_symmetry" title=3D"Reflecti=
on symmetry">reflection symmetry</a> in <i>n</i> axes that pass through the=
 center. If <i>n</i> is even then half of these axes pass through two oppos=
ite vertices, and the other half through the midpoint of opposite sides. If=
 <i>n</i> is odd then all axes pass through a vertex and the midpoint of th=
e opposite side.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Regular_convex_polygons">Re=
gular convex polygons</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DRegular_polygon&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit =
section: Regular convex polygons"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>All regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" tit=
le=3D"Simple polygon">simple polygons</a> (a simple polygon is one that doe=
s not intersect itself anywhere) are convex. Those having the same number o=
f sides are also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similarity_(geome=
try)" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">similar</a>.
</p><p>An <i>n</i>-sided convex regular polygon is denoted by its <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schl%C3%A4fli_symbol" title=3D"Schl=C3=A4=
fli symbol">Schl=C3=A4fli symbol</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-ma=
th-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a1=
1y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Mat=
hML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \{n\}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">{</mo>
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">}</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \{n\}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/335b6ca8393d83e990d21e637d1fd829b73f3971" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:3.72ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \{n\=
}}"></span>. For <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><=
span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display=
: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\di=
splaystyle n&lt;3}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mo>&lt;</mo>
        <mn>3</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n&lt;3}</anno=
tation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b44e690b54ac1146e95d07d8300f510b87848b9f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:5.656ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n&l=
t;3}"></span>, we have two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degener=
acy_(mathematics)" title=3D"Degeneracy (mathematics)">degenerate</a> cases:
</p>
<dl><dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monogon" title=3D"Monogon"=
>Monogon</a> {1}; point</dt>
<dd>Degenerate in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geomet=
ry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">ordinary space</a>. (Most authorities do n=
ot regard the monogon as a true polygon, partly because of this, and also b=
ecause the formulae below do not work, and its structure is not that of any=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_polytope" title=3D"Abstr=
act polytope">abstract polygon</a>.)</dd>
<dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digon" title=3D"Digon">Digon</=
a> {2}; line segment</dt>
<dd>Degenerate in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geomet=
ry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">ordinary space</a>. (Some authorities<sup =
class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:n=
owrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel=
_words" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wikipedia:Avoid weasel words"><span =
title=3D"Who says this? (December 2024)">weasel&nbsp;words</span></a></i>]<=
/sup> do not regard the digon as a true polygon because of this.)</dd></dl>
<p>In certain contexts all the polygons considered will be regular. In such=
 circumstances it is customary to drop the prefix regular. For instance, al=
l the faces of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_polyhedra" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform polyhedra">uniform polyhedra</a> mus=
t be regular and the faces will be described simply as triangle, square, pe=
ntagon, etc.
</p>
