class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=E2=81=A0</spa=
n><i>m</i>(<i>m</i> =E2=88=92 1)</span> parallelograms.
These tilings are contained as subsets of vertices, edges and faces in orth=
ogonal projections <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypercube" titl=
e=3D"Hypercube"><i>m</i>-cubes</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon#cite_note-8"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>In particular, this is true for any regular polygon with an even num=
ber of sides, in which case the parallelograms are all rhombi. Regular poly=
gons with 4m+2 sides can be dissected in a way with (2m+1)-fold radial symm=
etry.
The list <span class=3D"nowrap external"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/On-Line_Encyclopedia_of_Integer_Sequences" title=3D"On-Line Encyclop=
edia of Integer Sequences">OEIS</a>:&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://oeis.org/A0062=
45" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"oeis:A006245">A006245</a></span> gives the num=
ber of solutions for smaller polygons.
</p>
