<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Constructible_polygon">Cons=
tructible polygon</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DRegular_polygon&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Constructible polygon"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructible_polygo=
n" title=3D"Constructible polygon">Constructible polygon</a></div>
<p>Some regular polygons are easy to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Compass-and-straightedge_construction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Co=
mpass-and-straightedge construction">construct with compass and straightedg=
e</a>; other regular polygons are not constructible at all.
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Greek mathematics">ancient Greek mathematicians</a> kne=
w how to construct a regular polygon with 3, 4, or 5 sides,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Bold_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Regular_polygon#cite_note-Bold-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowr=
ap"><span title=3D"Page / location: p. xi">:=E2=80=8Ap. xi=E2=80=8A</span><=
/sup> and they knew how to construct a regular polygon with double the numb=
er of sides of a given regular polygon.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bold_13-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon#cit=
e_note-Bold-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"P=
age / location: pp. 49=E2=80=9350">:=E2=80=8App. 49=E2=80=9350=E2=80=8A</sp=
an></sup> This led to the question being posed: is it possible to construct=
 <i>all</i> regular <i>n</i>-gons with compass and straightedge? If not, wh=
ich <i>n</i>-gons are constructible and which are not?
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=
=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> proved the constructibil=
ity of the regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heptadecagon" t=
itle=3D"Heptadecagon">17-gon</a> in 1796. Five years later, he developed th=
e theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_period" title=
=3D"Gaussian period">Gaussian periods</a> in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Disquisitiones_Arithmeticae" title=3D"Disquisitiones Arit=
hmeticae">Disquisitiones Arithmeticae</a></i>. This theory allowed him to f=
ormulate a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sufficient_condition" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sufficient condition">sufficient condition</a=
> for the constructibility of regular polygons:
</p>
<dl><dd>A regular <i>n</i>-gon can be constructed with compass and straight=
edge if <i>n</i> is the product of a power of 2 and any number of distinct =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat_prime" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Fermat prime">Fermat primes</a> (including none).</dd></dl>
<p>(A Fermat prime is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_numb=
er" title=3D"Prime number">prime number</a> of the form <span class=3D"mwe-=
math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline=
 mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w=
3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 2^{\left(2^{n}\right)}+1.=
}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <msup>
                <mn>2</mn>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mi>n</mi>
                </mrow>
              </msup>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mn>1.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 2^{\left(2^{n=
}\right)}+1.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7768d938a1fc84fe9ba136b23dbded8c4eb37e51" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:9.111ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 2^{=
\left(2^{n}\right)}+1.}"></span>) Gauss stated without proof that this cond=
ition was also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Necessary_condition=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Necessary condition">necessary</a>, but ne=
ver published his proof. A full proof of necessity was given by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Wantzel" title=3D"Pierre Wantzel">Pier=
re Wantzel</a> in 1837. The result is known as the <b>Gauss=E2=80=93Wantzel=
 theorem</b>.
</p><p>Equivalently, a regular <i>n</i>-gon is constructible if and only if=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosine" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Cosine">cosine</a> of its common angle is a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructible_number" title=3D"Constructible number">co=
nstructible number</a>=E2=80=94that is, can be written in terms of the four=
 basic arithmetic operations and the extraction of square roots.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Regular_skew_polygons"><spa=
n class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Skew_regular_polygons"></span>Regular skew polygon=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_po=
lygon&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Regular sk=
ew polygons"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<table class=3D"wikitable" align=3D"right" width=3D"400">

<tbody><tr valign=3D"top">
<td><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:=
Cube_petrie_polygon_sideview.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D=
"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Cube_petrie_poly=
gon_sideview.svg/250px-Cube_petrie_polygon_sideview.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"160" height=3D"229" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"256" data-file-height=3D"366"></a></span><br>The <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube" title=3D"Cube">cube</a> contains a skew regular <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexagon" title=3D"Hexagon">hexagon</=
a>, seen as 6 red edges zig-zagging between two planes perpendicular to the=
 cube's diagonal axis.
</td>
<td><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:=
Antiprism17.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.w=
ikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Antiprism17.jpg/250px-Antiprism17=
.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"240" height=3D"144" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"877" data-file-height=3D"527"></a></span><br>The zi=
g-zagging side edges of a <i>n</i>-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Antiprism" title=3D"Antiprism">antiprism</a> represent a regular skew 2<i>=
n</i>-gon, as shown in this 17-gonal antiprism.
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>A <i>regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skew_polygon" titl=
e=3D"Skew polygon">skew polygon</a></i> in 3-space can be seen as nonplanar=
 paths zig-zagging between two parallel planes, defined as the side-edges o=
f a uniform <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiprism" title=3D"An=
tiprism">antiprism</a>. All edges and internal angles are equal.
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" width=3D"480">
<tbody><tr>
<td><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:=
Petrie_polygons.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Petrie_polygons.png/500px-Pet=
rie_polygons.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"480" height=3D"95" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2404" data-file-height=3D"474"></a></spa=
n><br>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D=
"Platonic solid">Platonic solids</a> (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Tetrahedron" title=3D"Tetrahedron">tetrahedron</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube" title=3D"Cube">cube</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octahedron" title=3D"Octahedron">octahedron</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dodecahedron" title=3D"Dodecahedron">=
dodecahedron</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosahedron"=
 title=3D"Icosahedron">icosahedron</a>) have Petrie polygons, seen in red h=
ere, with sides 4, 6, 6, 10, and 10 respectively.
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>More generally <i>regular skew polygons</i> can be defined in <i>n</i>-s=
pace. Examples include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petrie_=
polygon" title=3D"Petrie polygon">Petrie polygons</a>, polygonal paths of e=
dges that divide a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polytop=
e" title=3D"Regular polytope">regular polytope</a> into two halves, and see=
n as a regular polygon in orthogonal projection.
</p><p>In the infinite limit <i>regular skew polygons</i> become skew <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apeirogon" title=3D"Apeirogon">apeirogo=
ns</a>.
</p>
