<p>Depending on the precise derivation of the Schl=C3=A4fli symbol, opinion=
s differ as to the nature of the degenerate figure. For example, {6/2} may =
be treated in either of two ways:
</p>
<ul><li>For much of the 20th century (see for example <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon#CITEREFCoxeter1948">Coxeter (1948)</a>)=
, we have commonly taken the /2 to indicate joining each vertex of a convex=
 {6} to its near neighbors two steps away, to obtain the regular <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compound_polygon" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Compound polygon">compound</a> of two triangles, or <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexagram" title=3D"Hexagram">hexagram</a>. <div clas=
s=3D"paragraphbreak" style=3D"margin-top:0.5em"></div>Coxeter clarifies thi=
s regular compound with a notation {<i>kp</i>}[<i>k</i>{<i>p</i>}]{<i>kp</i=
>} for the compound {<i>p</i>/<i>k</i>}, so the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Hexagram" title=3D"Hexagram">hexagram</a> is represented as {=
6}[2{3}]{6}.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More compac=
tly Coxeter also writes 2{<i>n</i>/2}, like 2{3} for a hexagram as compound=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternation_(geometry)" title=
=3D"Alternation (geometry)">alternations</a> of regular even-sided polygons=
, with italics on the leading factor to differentiate it from the coincidin=
g interpretation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Many modern geometers, such as Gr=C3=BCnbaum (2003),<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Branko_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Regular_polygon#cite_note-Branko-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> regard this as incorrect. =
They take the /2 to indicate moving two places around the {6} at each step,=
 obtaining a "double-wound" triangle that has two vertices superimposed at =
each corner point and two edges along each line segment. Not only does this=
 fit in better with modern theories of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Abstract_polytope" title=3D"Abstract polytope">abstract polytopes</a>,=
 but it also more closely copies the way in which Poinsot (1809) created hi=
s star polygons =E2=80=93 by taking a single length of wire and bending it =
at successive points through the same angle until the figure closed.</li></=
ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Duality_of_regular_polygons=
">Duality of regular polygons</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DRegular_polygon&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=
=3D"Edit section: Duality of regular polygons"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<table class=3D"box-Expand_section plainlinks metadata ambox mbox-small-lef=
t ambox-content" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"mbox-image">=
<span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wiki=
