span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-dual_polyhedra" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Self-dual polyhedra">Self-dual polyhedra</a></d=
iv>
<p>All regular polygons are self-dual to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Congruency_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Congruency (ge=
ometry)">congruency</a>, and for odd <i>n</i> they are self-dual to identit=
y.
</p><p>In addition, the regular star figures (compounds), being composed of=
 regular polygons, are also self-dual.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Regular_polygons_as_faces_o=
f_polyhedra">Regular polygons as faces of polyhedra</h2><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_polygon&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Regular polygons as faces of polyhe=
dra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_polyhedron" title=3D"=
Uniform polyhedron">uniform polyhedron</a> has regular polygons as faces, s=
uch that for every two vertices there is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Isometry" title=3D"Isometry">isometry</a> mapping one into the ot=
her (just as there is for a regular polygon).
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasiregular_polyhedron" =
title=3D"Quasiregular polyhedron">quasiregular polyhedron</a> is a uniform =
polyhedron which has just two kinds of face alternating around each vertex.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polyhedron" title=
=3D"Regular polyhedron">regular polyhedron</a> is a uniform polyhedron whic=
h has just one kind of face.
</p><p>The remaining (non-uniform) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Convex_polyhedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Convex polyhedra">convex =
polyhedra</a> with regular faces are known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Johnson_solids" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Johnson soli=
ds">Johnson solids</a>.
</p><p>A polyhedron having regular triangles as faces is called a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltahedron" title=3D"Deltahedron">deltah=
edron</a>.
</p>
